04397nam a22006015i 9780520381162DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020029627  a9780520381162  a(DE-B1597)617182  a(OCoLC)1291506644  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aTK9152.16 4aTK9152.16 7aHIS0360702bisacsh04a363.17/9909732231 aWellock, Thomas R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSafe Enough? :bA History of Nuclear Power and Accident Risk /cThomas R. Wellock. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1 When Is a Reactor Safe? The Design Basis Accident -- t2 The Design Basis in Crisis -- t3 Beyond the Design Basis: The Reactor Safety Study -- t4 Putting a Number on “Safe Enough” -- t5 Beyond Design: Toward Risk-Informed Regulation -- t6 Risk Assessment Beyond the NRC -- t7 Risk-Informed Regulation and the Fukushima Accident -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the dawn of the Atomic Age, nuclear experts have labored to imagine the unimaginable and prevent it. They confronted a deceptively simple question: When is a reactor “safe enough” to adequately protect the public from catastrophe? Some experts sought a deceptively simple answer: an estimate that the odds of a major accident were, literally, a million to one. Far from simple, this search to quantify accident risk proved to be a tremendously complex and controversial endeavor, one that altered the very notion of safety in nuclear power and beyond. Safe Enough? is the first history to trace these contentious efforts, following the Atomic Energy Commission and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission as their experts experimented with tools to quantify accident risk for use in regulation and to persuade the public of nuclear power’s safety. The intense conflict over the value of risk assessment offers a window on the history of the nuclear safety debate and the beliefs of its advocates and opponents. Across seven decades and the accidents at Three Mile Island, Chernobyl, and Fukushima, the quantification of risk has transformed both society’s understanding of the hazards posed by complex technologies and what it takes to make them safe enough.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNuclear power plantsxRisk assessmentzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNuclear power plantszUnited StatesxSafety measures. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052038116240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520381162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520381162/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2021